Um what?? Vermeer’s “Girl with a Pearl” is moving from its home in @mauritshuis_museum to visit Amsterdam for a large Vermeer show! The museum is looking for paintings to display in its place!

Firstly, thank you @mauritshuis_museum for making clear in your submissions that artist retain their copyright, and this is for a fun community building opportunity for artists around the world who are, like me, deeply influenced by fine art history. ♥️

I made this painting in college during an oil painting course. My professor had the prompt “art history”. I had always been obsessed with Vermeer’s style, lighting, and liquid, silky brush strokes. That said, I wanted to have fun with the prompt ;)
When it was my turn for critique, I nervously put this painting up on the easel and went back to my seat. My professor KEELED over. I was concerned (he was older and had health problems). But quickly realized he keeled over from silently and hysterically laughing!! It was so out of character!!! 😅🥹🥰

The last thing my professor said to me in this class was that he believed I could be any artist I wanted to be. Animator, fine art— he told me I had the grit and the talent. He told me he believed in me.

You are missed, Professor Ernie Silva. Your gentle guidance and kindness lives forever in me. This painting sits in my studio proudly, never for sale. It is so precious to me. Your words and reaction to this painting is precious to me.

Behind the scenes! I knew the palette needed replacing because the paints were getting jelly like from a bit of neglect.

Not an ad, just a fan of @mastersonartproducts sta-wet painter palette! Paint is fluffing expensive and this tight seal container keeps my paint fresh for weeks on end, as long as I remember to sprints before and after use.

Also, @goldenpaints is the best quality acrylics I’ve ever used. My choice paints for #impawstos.

Words of encouragement for the budding poor artist— you don’t need brand name product to start your journey as an artists. TBH, my collection has been YEARS in the making. MANY tubes have been with me for over five years! Do not be discouraged and budget well for supplies. Many people are also willing to donate to community centers too! And supply quality is important but what’s more important is how you use the material. I started with student paint— the cheapest kind— and my brushes are still some original ones I’ve had my entire life. Slowly, I began to invest in the ever lasting quality goods. Budget well, and experiment with what you can afford!

And remember, it all started with a pencil and paper. Fancy doesn’t mean good. ♥️🥰

Made my soon to be 4 year old his birthday cake inspired by @pinterest!!

We looked up space cakes and he told me his favorite bits of every different cake. Must haves included: astronaut, our solar system planets IN ORDER 😅, and stars!

My husband baked all the goods! Vanilla cake, blueberry flavored frosting, shortbread cookies, and cookie icing. We did a less sweet version of everything and it was still sweet. Open to better frosting recipes if you have any!

I iced the cake, filled the layers with fresh blueberries, and carved a moon. Bottom layer was an oopsie icing using granulated sugar (which worked out for color) and top is a buttercream. I used a toothpick and frosting to pick out stars from a combo sprinkle pack and added them to the cake.

The next day I iced the shortbread cookies and assembled them with frosting inbetween to hold the skewers. After refrigerating for at least an hour, I assembled it all together!

He was very happy but not fully satisfied. “How do you like your cake buddy?!” “… where are the dwarf planets Pluto and Ceres?” 🤨

Moms never do anything right. 🤣 Part of me feels like he won’t remember this but part of me thinks he will because I’ll constant lot be shoving it in his face as he gets older. 😇 REMEMBER WHEN I MADE YOU THISSSSSS?!?!? 

Reminder for all moms, you do not need to be fancy. You don’t need to decorate a fluffing cake to be a good mom. You are a great mom for just being present. He was more excited for people singing happy birthday than anything else. It’s like boxes and kittens. 🙄

Trigger warning! CPTSD.

My first dream was to be a ballerina. I loved dancing. I thought ballerinas were the most graceful, inspiring humans.

When I shared my dream, I was told that I was too fat to be a ballerina. Too tall. They called me a little piggy in my leotard. I must have been 4 or 5, around my own child’s age right now. Needless to say, I stopped asking for dance class.  I developed binging habits and body dysmorphia that I’m still trying to correct. And now, looking at these photos, I am so enraged by how wrong those comments were.

CPTSD hit me hard in the middle of the day. I saw a viral video of an Asian American woman dancing with her dad. It was so unbelievably beautiful I got so triggered. I love seeing people have incredible relationships with their family, but sometimes triggers just hit you unexpectedly and HARD. I took a video of that raw moment but I’m too scared to share it right now because it’s too fresh, but I think it’s important, and I will when my heart can handle it.

Little Sheila, you are graceful. You are a dancer. You dance every morning with your child. Your husband grabs you to slow dance around the kitchen whenever a cute song plays on your morning playlist. You dance in your heart in every piece of art you work on. It gets better.

Keep dancing. Keep expressing. You are not too anything except too powerful for hurt people to handle. Your heart is immensely giving and you are healing at your own pace. You are worthy. You are loved. It gets better. 

My heart is giving this little girl the biggest embrace and sternest pep talk. I believe in you. I believe in you. I believe in YOU. 

It gets better.

If you or a loved one is struggling, please seek help. Please don’t give up. CPTSD is more common than many know and there are TOOLS to help you manage your triggers. A trigger like this use to debilitate me for weeks, but I recovered in minutes. I never imagined that was possible before. But that’s what happens after doing the work in therapy. You deserve to be healed, to be happy, to be loved. ♥️

From my first bouquet this season!

Tysm to my partner who encouraged me to redo a few when I felt dismayed. Funny enough, most my clients liked my first version that I wasn’t a fan of 🤣 Goes to show, art is VERY subjective.

Though I consider myself a seasoned artist now, the doubts still exist. When clients are rude about their artwork (0.0005%, we calculated it) it feels like everyone is upset at me. (Not to be confused with people who might not be happy but are kind in asking for edits! That makes it 0.05%) I have to do the numbers to make me see factual evidence that I’m doing okay.

I’ve heard it all. “It’s not worth it, save your money.” “It’s ugly, she’s not that good” “so-and-so could do better” — all either right to my face or in front of my team. And those are just the ones we hear.

If I let opinions from people who are CLEARLY not my ideal clients, I would never do digital art. I wouldn’t be making portraits out of flowers or matcha or coffee. I’d be doing fine art only still, which is undervalued and underpaid and over saturated and falsely advertised by AI/digital artists claiming them to be “handmade”. I would let every mistake feel like a massive failure instead of a learning moment. No one has time for all that doubt and self sabotaging! 

I love my furever florals. Last year only a few people were interested because it was a new concept. After doing latte art, clients are more use to the concept and idea. Now I am meeting my minimum quota every bouquet to make it worth while. Sometimes it’s not your art that is the problem— it’s the marketing of it and client understanding of what you offer. It just takes time and pivots to get it right.

Nothing is more valuable than the opinions of your dream clients. Nothing is more creatively important than sticking to your artistic instincts. Trust the people who have EARNED a spot at the table.

And to all the others? Nothing is more detrimental than letting their words matter. They weren’t rooting for you in the first place. Shine on without them.

We bought an espresso machine early this year (largely influenced by @kristinechenceramics) and I was determined to learn the art of lattes to pay this investment off 🤣. I made a spreadsheet to justify the purchase to my husband, with the pitch that the one thing we need if we were going to try and expand our family would be energy. Coffee would give us energy. Great coffee would give us great energy. Looking back 2 months postpartum, I would like to give past Sheila a tearful hug and say thank you for making that choice 🤣🤣🤣

Wins: adding a new medium to my skill set is always a win!! This one was particularly challenging. Not only do I need to be precise in my illustration, but my latte making skills needed to be on par as well! That was a huge learning curve!! Foam @oatly too much, it bubbles the art. Foam it too little and it’s not enough to illustrate or hold the art. I am proud of how this medium continues to improve every cup 🫶🏼

Failures: packaging was an issue! Some clients didn’t know that photo paper is very fragile, so the sticky part of the cover would get onto the photo paper and remove ink 🫣. We learned to put a sheet of tissue paper over the artwork to ensure a safe transfer! Tysm to the clients who reached out about the problem!!! I was also posting daily/monthly availability and I found daily to be too stressful and monthly to be too long. Clients would be upset about waiting even if they knew the turnaround time.

Now the machine is paid off 🫶🏼 and I will be posting weekly spots! It’s a good medium! Our @onyxcoffeelab brews keep mom and dad fueled for taking care of two littles and two furbs, and our @ascasousa machine is now treated like a family member 🤣🤣🤣

*trigger warning, PPD self harm*

Lately I’ve been thinking about my self worth.
Giving birth, seeing your son tied up in tubes for that first raw month of motherhood… I haven’t been able to process it. Followed by holidays at home with a toddler and COVID while struggling with painful early days of breastfeeding… I haven’t been able to process it. Followed by disappointments, frustrations, loss, grief, guilt, being manipulated in my most vulnerable state.. I haven’t processed it.

I need to process it. I need to honor my needs. I need to feel like I matter.

These illustrations were made in my early days of pursuing a life as an artist— before diving into pet portraits. I didn’t know what my future was. I was scared, I was depressed, I was lonely and desperate to figure things out.

Years later I can look back at these illustrations and see my heart as it always has been. I can see my artwork and be reminded of how proud I am of her. I’m proud of her will, her tenacity, her vulnerability, her deep desires to do good. She’s unknown, not a penny to her name… and look at what she can make in her worst state. She is beautiful.

Depression isn’t something to be afraid of. You can’t control what hand you’re dealt, but you can take control of how you play it. Intrusive thoughts of your life not mattering, the out of body experience of thinking the world is better without you in it… sometimes it’s okay to get deeply in a bad place because it jolts you into fighting to being okay again.

It’s okay to talk about it. It’s okay to feel it. It’s okay to be scared. It’s okay to be human. I’m not perfect. I lack tact, always 🤣. I can be jealous, petty, mean— especially when sleep deprived and scared. I am a work in progress and sometimes a mistake on a canvas. Experience has taught me to catch those mistakes earlier, deal with it sooner. Experience has given me tools to do it better.

I have post partum depression. I go from happy to weepy with a simple thought. I’m taking the next week or longer to process my experience, and I know I’ll be back stronger than ever. 🫶🏼

Thank you for simply being here. You make me want to be here, too.
